reviewText:
Of course I'm going to buy it!  This has got to be the first great cartoon of the 21st century, and I'm one of the adult "Spongebob underground."  That is, the adults out there who watch this show but are afraid to tell any of their adult friends for fear of being laughed at.
Now, it's a bit annoying that after collecting several Spongebob DVD's, they come out with this collection so soon.  I'm getting to where I'll never buy individual DVDs of a TV series again, because this happens over and over.  If a show is phenominally popular, ignore everything untill the season-at-a-time box sets come out.  I've got the message.
Now, how about the folks at Nick releasing some of the earlier classics.  How about a Ren and Stimpy box set, or a Rocko's Modern Life box set?  What fun those would be!

Why didn't they do this in the first place!!!!??????
I am a huge fan of the show. But I am pretty mad at Nick right now for first releasing sponge DVDs with the episodes all mixed up and not according to season, and they decide NOW, after seven (the seventh actually comes out on 9/30) of these DVDs, to release it according to season. I own the first six, and now I'll have to sell them used. What a waste of money. Sorta. The Season One set will be a great buy. It's not my favorite season (2, represent!), but it's great all the same. Here's the special features!
90 minutes of extras, INCLDUING:
-The Origin of Spongebob SquarePants
-Recollection from the 1st season crew featurette
-Everybody's talking: The voices of Spongebob SquarePants
-The Bikini Bottoms Up Tour
-In the key of Sea: Krusty Krab Karaoke
-Audio Commentary with Cast discussing 2 of their favorite episodes
-3 Music Videos
Sounds like a whoppin' good DVD set. Now I gotta go clean the disks of the old DVDs and ship 'em off to eBay. Buh-bye!
Also, watch for the SpongeBob movie on November 19, 2004. And stay tuned to Nick for new SpongeBob episodes next year, including "SpongeBob B.C." (Before Comedy), aka "Ugh". It's a half-hour Patchy special in which SpongeBob, Patrick, and Squidward discover fire. Oh, great, I sound like a news reporter guy.

Here comes the first season of the cult smash that's fun for kids and adults alike. Spongebob's peculiar charm came from nowhere into one of the most beloved cartoons of recent times and finally we have the complete first season on DVD, instead of the numerous compilations already out. (when will they realize people really want TV released by seasons)

Along with the Oresteia, Beethoven's 5th, and the Sistine Chapel this piece of craftsmanship is one of the greatest masterpieces of western civilization. It is full of themes that ring true across time and cultures alike. The sheer amount of artistry that went into forging this timeless tale of this unforgettable yellow sponge is unfathomable. This is why Stephen Hillenburg will be remembered with greats such as Plato, Shakespeare, and Goethe as those luminaries who were able, unlike so many others, to transcend the filth of this world and reach towards the eternal forms of true art. In fact I cannot recall a single piece with such rich character development and novel plot-lines as the opening season of Spongebob Squarepants. In closing I would say to all those contemplating whether Spongebob is worth their time: THIS SHOW WILL CAUSE YOU TO EXPERIENCE YOUR HUMANITY IN WAYS YOU COULD NEVER BEFORE COMPREHEND... DO NOT MISS THIS OPPORTUNITY TO LIVE FULLY AS A HOMO SAPIEN

SpongeBob SquarePants Season 1 is only pure, silly entertainment. Do not expect it to be educational public television. With that being said we baby sit our 1 1/2 year old and he loves it. One of the first few words he spoke was "Ponge Bob".

We watch it on both from the Nickelodeon App our Apple TV and our Amazon Fire Stick. Both have merits. Show on the Apple TV are shown in full HD screen with a great picture, BUT there are Nickelodeon commercials. Spongebob on our Amazon Firestick play episodes back to back without commercials, BUT the picture is in standard definition with the black bars on the sides of the screen.

We've watched every episode so many times that we've memorized almost every line and its obvious that the writers anticipate some of the humor going over the children's heads and is aimed at the adults watching with them.

As a final note, when my wife worked at a Christian School this was one of the forbidden cartoons to show at after school. If you have to judge that type of thing, watch the episode at night before watching it with your child. Don't ban an entire series because of one or two scenes.

Was dragged kicking and screaming to the TV while being forced to watch with my grand kids.  Pleasantly surprised and after the first few episodes I became a fan.  Very clever.  Primary characters' expressive animation is well done (and a little over the top).  Many references to old TV shows about which kids would have no clue.  Maybe that's a nod for adults dragged kicking and screaming to the TV.  It's fun to exercise the kids' brains with obvious impossibilities - like underwater swimming pools and fires.  Was nice to genuinely laugh at a TV show for a change. No gutter talk, innuendos, political propaganda or a phony laugh track.  Quite refreshing, actually.  I hope future episodes don't succumb to the usual Hollywood tilt.

Somewhere in Europe, the German DVD re-release of SpongeBob SquarePants: The Complete First Season does live up to its name. Let's explain that. In North America the Region 1 DVD releases doesn't have the very first episode called Help Wanted, because it contains an oldies song (Livin' in the Sunlight, Lovin' in the Moonlight) by Tiny Tim. That episode can only be found on 10 Happiest Moments DVD, and The First 100 Episodes Box Set. However, the German release does have very first episode which makes their set the most definitive release in the world and in English and German dubbed[]. Alongside all of the episodes from the first season, the DVD authoring playback of these episodes isn't marathon mode but feels just like broadcast version. So what's the point? It's SpongeBob as we all know it, NTSC or not! : SpongeBob Schwammkopf - Die komplette Season 1 -- PAL Region 2

Otherwise,  I think most of the episodes are okay, Sponge Bob in general just annoys me since he enjoys watching it SO much.  It is definitely his most favorite cartoon, so that is why I haven't cut it out of the programs he watches altogether.  I'm not sure if the producers or creators of this cartoon ever look over these reviews, but if you do PLEASE omit the words and phrases that are absolutely unnecessary to include in a child's television progam! In 1999 Nickelodeon debuted "SpongeBob Squarepants" and to this day it still is entertaining and funny. Originally intended to be called "SpongeBoy Ahoy!", it tells the story of a manmade sponge, his friends and various misadventures in Bikini Bottom. The first season contains many favorites including "Ripped Pants", "Suds" and my personal favorite "Jellyfishing". The only complaint one would make is the original pilot episode isn't included due to licensing issues. But none the less this is a nice DVD set, it includes select episode commentary, and storyboards.
Technical Specifications:
English Stereo
Aspect Ratio: 1.33:1 (Original Broadcast Ratio)
Rating: TV-Y7 (United States), PG (Canadian Home Video rating)

If you've never seen Sponge Bob nor understood the phrase, "Pinky Up!" then you are in for a treat.  This classic first season introduces you to the outrageous and zany deep sea denizens of Bikini Bottom which center around the crazy adventures of the main character Sponge Bob, a lowly, fry cook in a burger joint called the Krusty Krab owned by a crustacean obviously named Mr. Krab and his fellow employee and neighbor, Squidword.  There are other characters essential to success of this cartoon such as Patrick the Starfish, Sandy the Squirrel, Mrs Puff the Boat Driving School teacher, Plankton, the rival fast food restaurant owner aptly named by his generous stature and Davy Jones, the Ghost Pirate Captain.  It is just the ridiculousness and silliness of the show that adds to its charm and success.  Adults should watch first to gauge the humour which can sometimes be a little much for Pre K but all other ages are fine.

This is the complete first season of the SpongeBob Squarepants series. You get 3 discs.

Episodes:

DISC ONE
Reef Blower/Tea At the Treedome - SpongeBob uses his new reef blower/SpongeBob visits his new friend Sandy at her water-free home

Bubblestand/Ripped Pants - SpongeBob gives Squidward lessons on how to blow bubbles/SpongeBob accidentally rips his pants at the beach

Jellyfishing/Plankton! - SpongeBob and Patrick take Squidward jellyfishing/Plankton tries to trick SpongeBob into giving him the Krabby Patty secret formula

Naughty Nautical Neighbors/Boating School - Squidward creates a fight between SpongeBob and Patrick/Patrick helps SpongeBob cheat on his boating exam

Pizza Delivery/Home Sweet Pineapple - SpongeBob and Squidward deliver the first ever Krusty Krab pizza/After a pack of nematodes eat SpongeBob's pineapple, he must find a new home

Mermaidman and Barnacle Boy/Pickles - SpongeBob and Patrick visit their heroes Mermaidman and Barnacle Boy/SpongeBob forgets how to make a Krabby Patty after forgetting to put pickles on a customer's sandwich

Hall Monitor/Jellyfish Jam - SpongeBob takes his duty as the boating school hall monitor a little too seriously/SpongeBob jams all night with his jellyfish friends

Sandy's Rocket/Squeaky Boots - SpongeBob and Patrick take Sandy's rocket to hunt for aliens on the moon/Mr. Krabs gives SpongeBob a pair of boots which never stop squeaking

DISC TWO
Nature Pants/Opposite Day - SpongeBob decides he wants to go live with the jellyfish/Squidward tricks SpongeBob into thinking it's Opposite Day so he can sell his house

Culture Shock/F.U.N. - SpongeBob becomes the unlikely star of Squidward's talent show/SpongeBob tries to show Plankton a good time

MuscleBob BuffPants/Squidward the Unfriendly Ghost - SpongeBob tries to impress Sandy by getting fake muscles/Squidward has a little fun with SpongeBob and Patrick after they think they have accidentally killed Squidward

The Chaperone/Employee of the Month - SpongeBob accompanies Pearl to her prom/SpongeBob and Squidward compete to win Employee of the Month

Scaredy Pants/I Was A Teenage Gary - SpongeBob makes an attempt to be scary on Halloween/SpongeBob accidentally gets injected with Gary's medicine

SB-129/Karate Choppers - Squidward travels in time to get away from SpongeBob/Mr. Krabs forbids SpongeBob and Sandy to practice karate

Sleepy Time/Suds - SpongeBob travels through everyone's dreams/SpongeBob is afraid to go to the doctor

Valentine's Day/The Paper - SpongeBob has a big Valentine's Day surprise for Patrick/SpongeBob shows Squidward all the fun things to do with a piece of paper

DISC THREE
Arrgh!/Rock Bottom - SpongeBob and Patrick follow Mr. Krabs on a treasure hunt/SpongeBob gets lost in Rock Bottom and has difficulty in catching a bus back home

Texas/Walking Small - Sandy is homesick/Plankton tries to get SpongeBob to help him take over the beach with his new restaurant

Fools In April/Neptune's Spatula - Squidward plays a mean prank on SpongeBob for April Fool's Day/SpongeBob becomes King Neptune's new fry cook

Hooky/Mermaidman and Barnacle Boy II - SpongeBob and Patrick play with fisherman's hooks/SpongeBob wins Mermaidman and Barnacle Boy's conch shell in a contest and abuses its power

BONUS FEATURES
SpongeBob Squarepants Montage Trailer (Disc 1)
The Origin of SpongeBob Squarepants
Recollections from the First Season Crew
Everybody's Talking: The Voices of SpongeBob Squarepants
The Bikini Bottoms Up Tour
In the Key of Sea: Krusty Krab Karaoke
Drawing Goo Lagoon
SpongeBob's Life Strategies
Violent Femmes Sing SpongeBob
SpongeBob Scaredy Pants
SpongeBob Dancin' Pants
Cast Commentary on Plankton! and Karate Choppers

* Please note the pilot episode Help Wanted is not included in this set. I believe it is a bonus feature on Season 3.

As we get older, we tend to think Spongebob and his mooching friend Patrick are kind of the j***s, and Squidward is a little more sympathetic (though actually, Squidward is tiresome in his own way too).  Spongebob represents the injustices a kid feels in an adult world.  The other characters are common annoyances we know in the adult world--the guy who is obsessed with money, the cool friend who is fun but is a deadbeat and hangs around in his underwear all the time, the pseudo-intellectual who thinks he is better than everybody, the country girl who can beat all the boys chops, etc.

In honor of SpongeBob's 15th anniversary in 2014, here's my review of the very first season of one of my all-time fave Nicktoons, besides Digimon and Rugrats. Due to legal confusion, the original pilot episode "Help Wanted" isn't in this set, neither in the original bulky packaging nor in the new single-case packaging, but they are together in The First 100 Episodes set. However, its 2 partner episodes remain, along with the other 19 pairs of episodes! This set has a huge amount of bonus features, more than any other season set, most of which are on the last disc. (Help Wanted is a bonus episode in season 3's set!) From SpongeBob getting his job at the Krusty Krab, to he and Patrick making friends with Sandy Cheeks, to the start of the Mermaidman and Barnacleboy saga, to SpongeBob's first Halloween classics (Scaredy Pants and I Was A Teenage Gary) and the only official Valentine special, and his April Fools' bonanza, and Squidward's bold glimpses of the future and distant past (and in another dimension), it's (almost) all here in glorious Traditional-cel animation! Season 1 was the only season of SpongeBob to be made this way. Just as Digimon did, SpongeBob was slowly-but-surely gaining popularity when both shows were brand-new in 1999 and 2000. In SpongeBob's case, his universal appeal was catching on to kids and grownups alike, all over the world, just like Mickey Mouse himself! The only thing that bugs me about this set is the picture seems to lag in many episodes compared to when they were seen on Nick, before they sped up most of the episodes of all 9 seasons for more commercial time! Steve Hillenburg created something pretty darn special all right, being a former crew member of Rocko's Modern Life, just like Tom Kenny and Mr. Lawrence were in those days. In fact, in "The Chaperone", Tom Kenny used his Heffer Wolfe voice on one of the dancers after kicking out SpongeBob and Pearl from the prom. If you wanna see how the most popular Nicktoon in history got his start, season 1 is a great choice, and the First 100 Episodes set is even greater, if it weren't being priced so high in 2014! Alongside Mickey, Bugs Bunny, Tom and Jerry, Popeye, the Pink Panther, Winnie the Pooh, and lots of other all-time greats in toon history, SpongeBob truly is among them! And season 1 will get you started despite not having its pilot episode in this set.

Mom:  I have been subjected to SpongeBob for many, many years. I have an 18 year old and 14 year old who watched this program and now a 6 year old that enjoys this program. I would love to say that I look forward to viewing this program, but at best I am impartial as you see, far better children's programming from 15 years ago has gone away while SpongeBob still goes on. I never dreamed I would after years of watching children's programming still be enduring this cartoon. I do not understand it, except that SpongeBob is heavily marketed to children. The graphics and colors are bright, and there do seem to be some morals and lessons that kids will learn from. The story line is sometimes weird and sometimes funny. A redeeming quality of the program is that the adult humor in it is (mostly) not inappropriate nor do they talk about sex in every single sentence or put other people down. Except SpongeBob of course. Who always comes back with a smile and ends up on top of the situation. Perhaps that is the secret and why it appeals to small children. SpongeBob does appear to have the mental and emotional capacity of a 6 year old. He trusts everyone (and he should not), he has many friends (he believes), and he is really great at everything (no he is not), and all the while he goes along with his plan with great intentions oblivious to the entire world falling apart around him. It also ends on a happy note within about 23 minutes which is just enough time to have an after school snack.
Daughter:  I love SpongeBob and Patrick.

SpongeBob Squarepants is much more than a cartoon...he is a cultural icon. The smart writing is what allows this show to transcend the trappings of a children's show and become the witty smart show that it is. For the aforementioned reasons, I enthusiastically give this show five out of five stars. If I could have, I would have given it more stars.

I LOVE SPONGEBOB, because he is funny and I have been watching this show since 1999 I was only 14 years old that time. 15 years later, The humor and the silliness never changed. SpongeBob is still popular, is still a favorite to kids and adults alike and I am 28 years old now and I am still a fan of SpongeBob. This season introduces the characters: SpongeBob Squarepants, the main character of the entire series, who lives in a pineapple under the sea. Patrick Star, SpongeBob's dim witted best friend. Squidward Tentacles, SpongeBob's grumpy, stuck up, and snob next door neighbor. Gary, SpongeBob's pet meowing snail. Sandy Cheeks, SpongeBob's friend who is a land squirrel. Mr. Krabs, SpongeBob's greedy and cheap boss of the Krusty Krab. Plankton, Mr. Krabs' arch rival. Mermaidman and Barnacleboy, SpongeBob's and Patrick's favorite retired heroes. Miss Puff, SpongeBob's boating teacher. Pearl, Mr. Krabs' teenage whale daughter.  This box set had all of the season 1 episodes except Help Wanted in 3 dvds and here is the complete guide.

Disc 1

(Help Wanted. (Not included in this set). Introduces SpongeBob, Squidward, and Mr. Krabs. SpongeBob wants to work at Krusty Krab, a fast food joint as a chef. Squidward and Krabs sent SpongeBob to get a spatula which does not exist until a overwhelming school of anchovies show up and it is up to SpongeBob to save the day.)

1. Reef Blower. Introduction of SpongeBob and Squidward. After Squidward kicks a stray shell to SpongeBob's yard, he had to use a reef blower, a parody of a leaf blower to get rid of it.

2. Tea at the Treedome. Introduction of Sandy Cheeks, Sandy invites SpongeBob to her home. Due to misguided advice from Patrick, he does not know that sea animals cannot breath in land.

3. Bubblestand. SpongeBob sets up lessons how to blow a bubble until it annoys Squidward so much and he pays to learn how to blow a bubble until he takes the lesson too far.

4. Ripped Pants. SpongeBob accidently rips his pants at the beach and he become a big hit, but SpongeBob took his fame too far and his fame annoyed everyone at the beach included Sandy.

5. Jellyfishing. One of my favorites. SpongeBob and his friend Patrick started to play jellyfishing, a parody of fishing, with Squidward and it leads him in a body cast and a wheelchair.

6. Plankton. One of my favorites. Introduction of Plankton. Plankton had planned to steal a krabby patty from Mr. Krabs for years. He planned to go inside SpongeBob's brain, controls him, and bring a krabby patty to the Chum Bucket.

7. Naughty Nautical Neighbors. After beginning annoyed by SpongeBob's and Patrick's bubble communication and laughter, Squidward plans to break them up, but disaster strikes to Squidward.

8. Boating School. introduction of Miss Puff. After failed many times at his boating exam, SpongeBob plans to cheat the exam with Patrick by a radio in his head.

9. Pizza Delivery. After getting a call from a customer who wants a pizza from the Krusty Krab, Squidward told Krabs that they do not sell pizza. Oh really? Krabs made one. He told SpongeBob and Squidward to delivery the pizza and they end in many hilarious situations.

10. Home Sweet Pineapple. Nematodes ate SpongeBob's home and he plans to move in with his parents which is delight to Squidward.

11. Mermaidman and Barnacleboy. SpongeBob and Patrick want their favorite heroes to come out of retirement and they keep annoy them until they fight their goofy fans.

12. Pickles. Introduction of Bubble Bass. SpongeBob become devastated when he found out there are no pickles in Bubble Bass' krabby patty. It causes SpongeBob to lose his confidence to make a krabby patty and it is up to Krabs to save the day.

13. Hall Monitor. After selected as a Hall Monitor by Miss Puff, SpongeBob takes his duty too far.

14. Jellyfish Jam. SpongeBob takes a jelly fish home, but the jelly fish is too wild for SpongeBob to own, the jelly fish partied too hard, and it is up to Gary to save the day.

15. Sandy's Rocket. SpongeBob and Patrick steal Sandy's rocket ship, so they can learn if aliens exist in the moon.

16. Squeaky Boots. Introduction of Pearl. Pearl gets a pair of rubber boots from her cheap father at her birthday. Krabs convinces SpongeBob to keep the boots if he gave up his paycheck. He does not know that he made a mistake and he loses it whenever he hears a squeaking sound.

Disc 2

17. Nature Pants. SpongeBob quits his job, so he can live with the jelly fish. Due to Mr. Krabs' warning, SpongeBob realize that he cannot live like a jelly fish.

18. Opposite Day. Fed up with SpongeBob's and Patrick's childish antics, Squidward made up a holiday, so he can sell his house to keep SpongeBob and Patrick away from him and the seller until his plan backfires.

19. Culture Shock. Due to few customers, Krabs and Squidward set up a talent show, so they can get more customers.

20. F.U.N. SpongeBob thinks Plankton is lonely, so he convinces him to be his friend. It is an act all along, so Plankton can steal a krabby patty from SpongeBob.

21. MuscleBob BuffPants. Tired of weak, SpongeBob orders a pair of inflatable muscle arms, but they are no help in muscle contests, only for lying.

22. Squidward the Unfriendly Ghost. After SpongeBob thinks he "kills" Squidward, Patrick convinces SpongeBob that Squidward is a vengeful spirit, so Squidward must to put to rest.

23. The Chaperone. After getting dumped by her boyfriend, SpongeBob takes Pearl to the prom, but disaster strikes at midnight.

24. Employee of the Month. SpongeBob and Squidward compete for the Employee of the Month, but they took it too far.

25. Scaredy Pants. Introduction of the Flying Dutchman. It is Halloween and tired of anyone calling him scaredy pants, SpongeBob dresses up as the Flying Dutchman for revenge.

26. I Was a Teenage Gary. After Squidward forgets to fed Gary, SpongeBob and Squidward are turned into snails from a serum.

27. SB-129, Fed up with SpongeBob and Patrick questioning about going jellyfishing, Squidward locked himself in a freezer and he met his worst nightmare in different timelines.

28. Karate Choppers. Fed up with SpongeBob's karate antics, Krabs forbids SpongeBob using karate or he will lose his job.

29. Sleepy Time. SpongeBob trespasses the Bikini Bottom citizen's dreams and gives them nightmares.

30. Suds. SpongeBob gets the suds after forgetting to close the fridge door. Patrick tries to cure SpongeBob, so he can't go to the doctor.

31. Valentine's Day. After Patrick believes that SpongeBob forgot a Valentine's gift for him, Patrick loses it and goes buck wild at a theme park.

32. The Paper. After Squidward threw a gum wrapper, SpongeBob start to play with it. It causes Squidward to be impressed and he will trade everything even his house and his shirt to get it back.

Disc 3

33. Arrgh! Krabs takes a treasure hunting game too seriously.

34. Rock Bottom. SpongeBob gets in the wrong bus and he was trapped in a scary city with the worst bus service ever.

35. Texas. Feeling homesick, Sandy wants to go back to Texas and it is up to SpongeBob and Patrick will do anything even anger her to convince her that Bikini Bottom is her home.

36. Walking Small. Plankton plans to turn the beach into a new Chum Bucket Mega Bucket and the beachgoers refuse to leave. Plankton recruits SpongeBob to disappoint the beachgoers, so they can leave.

37. Fools in Aprils. Annoyed with SpongeBob's childish pranks, Squidward attempts to prank SpongeBob, but he goes too far.

38. Neptune's Spatula. One of my favorites. Introduction of King Neptune. At a museum, SpongeBob pulls the golden spatula from a ancient grease and King Neptune challenges SpongeBob.

39. Hooky. When SpongeBob and Patrick did not listen to Krabs' warning about the hooks, he had no choice but to teach them a lesson about hooks, shops, and the smell of mayonnaise.

40. Mermaidman and Barnacleboy II. When SpongeBob wins the Conch Signal, he calls his favorite heroes to do his childish antics and the Conch Signal was supposed to be used in emergencies only.

Sponge Bob is a hit or miss with me.  Some episodes are funny and appropriate for kids, others are just flat out gross or are really kind of too old for the targeted viewers (Y7 rated).  Examples of that are:  "Bubblestand" where SpongeBob open's his version of a Lemonade Stand and takes request of what the customer would like to seen made from bubbles.....then tries to teach Squidward how to do it after several failed attempts.  Its funny and shows how to help other's who need help and encouraging when things aren't working out for the one having trouble.  Now "The Suds" is one that is gross and while tries to show a good moral, still was very gross.  SpongeBob is sick but is scared by Patrick to go to the Doctor's and just ends up getting sicker and sicker (Suds are what we call a common cold) so there are a handful of gross parts that personally I find to be a little much.

There are characters for everyone to relate to or like:
SpongeBob is the carefree, hardworking, loyal friend and employee who wants to do everything he can to help people and just enjoy everyday to the fullest.
Patrick Star is the loyal friend who is well not the brightest light bulb but is another carefree loyal friend.  He sometimes tries to be helpful but ends up making more of a mess our of the situation.
Gary is SpongeBob's faithful companion.  Instead of a dog or cat, he is a snail, and has the attitude of Garfield with dealing with John or Odie.  Very funny character.
Mr. Krabs who is SpongeBob's boss of "The Krusty Krab" loves his money and will do anything to make a penny but all in all has a good heart.....if he hasn't sold it for more money.
Plankton who is Mr. Krabs arch enemy run the rival restaurant "The Chum Bucket" is always trying to steal the precious formula to Mr. Krabs famous burger.
Finally there is Squidward, the grumpy, dry humor person who always dreams of his big life that he'll have but yet is still stuck at the "Krusty Krab" day dreaming of bigger things.  He has his moments of caring but does his best not to show it.

So as a 34-year old guy, I have resigned myself to having one guilty pleasure and that's Spongebob Squarepants.  I find this cartoon to be just plain funny.  The characters are amusingly outlandish, the stories are (mostly) mindless, and the animation is classic "kid-animation".  Whenever I'm in need of a good laugh or some levity, Spongebob never fails to deliver.  I look forward to watching the rest of the seasons!  Who can I recommend this to?  No one in particular, as the crazy humor may not appeal to everyone.  I can just recommend that you try watching a couple of episodes and see if it's your cup of tea.  I didn't imagine I would like it as much as I do, but now that I've been exposed to it I have to say it is one of the funniest shows I have seen. This Is One of The Best Spongebob DVDs Out There. The 1st Season is The Best Season of Them All! Spongebob is One of The Better Cartoons Out There Now-A-Days. I'm Now Starting To Collect All The Spongebob Box Sets At The Moment, So It May Take A While Until I Review and Get Them All.

Anyways, On To The Review.

Episodes Include:

Reef Blower - A Short Including Spongebob Anoying Squidward With A Brand New Reef Blower. For The First Ever Short Episode For Spongebob (Though Not The Best) It's A Great Short and The Humor Happens With No Words Just Random Gags Happening With Nothing Except Noises With A Reef Blower. (5/5)

Tea At The Treedome - The First Episode Involving Sandy, In Which Spongebob Is Invied To Sandy's Home Which Is A Dome With Air and Spongebob Starts Having A Hard Time Breathing. Though I'm Giving The Prouduct Five Stars, This One of The Few Episodes That I Felt Was Missing Something. Not The Best From Spongebob. (2/5)

Bubblestand - Spongebob Opens A Stand Where Fish Can Blow Bubbles For 25 Cents. After Squidward Can't Stand It No More He Tries Spongebob's Bubblestand and Tries It Out. One of The Best Spongebob Episode Made and It Succedes Yet Again. (5/5)

Ripped Pants - A Hilarious Episode Involving Spongebob Ripping His Pants His Pants For A Cheap Laugh At Goo Lagoon, But The Laugh Wares Off, And FAST! The Best of The 1st Season Which Also Includes One of The Silliest (Yet Catchy) Singing  Moments in Animated History. (5/5)

Jellyfishing - Squidward Ends Up Jellyfishing With Spongebob and Patrick After A Bikcyle Acciedent, Which Spongebob and Patrick Think This Would Make Him Better, But Squidward Has Been Having A Horrible Day and This Dosn't Even Make Him Better. An Absolutely Great Episode (Though Not As Great as ''Squidville'') and It Contains What Might Be One of The Best Endings in Spongebob History. (4/5)

Plankton - The First Episode That Indroduces Plankton Who In This Episode Tries To Control Spongebob's Brain To Get The Krabby Patty Formula. Plankton Is One of The Best Carecters on The Show and He is Like The Carecter Brain From Pinky snd The Brain. The Episode Also  Includes A Commentary. (5/5)

They live for Spongebob, Patrick, Squidward, Mr. Krabs, Gary, Sandy, and Mrs. Puff.

But I don't and can't blame them really; Spongebob is a catch and from time to time, the show itself is actually quite funny. It all takes place at Bikini Bottom, a town underwater, away from most sharks and beneath all the humans who dwell on earth. From time to time, Spongebob and Patrick make it a rare habit to come up out of the water, and take a looksee around. Immediately, they puff up like Mrs. Puff, Spongebob's driving teacher. He never learns how to drive successfully either. He's no good in that department, and should stick to the Krabby Patties!

Anyway, I'm gonna describe and then rate all of the characters and then rate a few aspects of the actual film:

Spongebob Squarepants: Very silly, upbeat and so nice to everyone that is nice to him. Even if you're mean, he tries to see the good in everyone. My second favorite character. A

Patrick Star: Super goofy and kinda spaced out, he's basically Spongebob's right-hand man. His personality, while goofy, consists of being nice to Spongebob but he tends to have an anger spout here and there. An OK character. B-

Squidward Tentacles: Another keeper, character-wise. He's the moody, selfish and very negative critic of the series. Many enjoy his company, especially Spongebob, but funnily, Squidward doesn't feel half the happiness when around the yellow sponge. He'd rather have his hands around his neck, doing the unthinkable. B+

Mr. Krabs: Very work-oriented, and a decent man who tries to instill the work ethic into Spongebob and Squidward also. Spongebob follows, and Squidward carries on, as if Mr. Krabs said NOTHING. Not one of my favorite characters. C-

Gary: My absolute favorite! I can't really pinpoint a true-blue personality to him, but he makes cat sounds, is usually quiet, which leads me to believe that he's an introvert as opposed to an extrovert, and loves Spongebob till the ends of the sandy ends of Bikini Bottom. A+

Pearl Krabs: The whiny, big-headed whale-daughter of Mr. Krabs. She's so ridiculously spoiled that I would slap her if I was an imaginary fish, residing in Bikini Bottom. She's not a bad character, and is usually super-dramatic. B+

Sandy: Level-headed and sweet, Sandy is nearly as friendly as Spongebob. Get on her bad side though, and she's unafraid to show you a piece of her mind! B

Mrs. Puff: She holds one of the absolute worst jobs in Bikini Bottom; trying to teach the unteachable Spongebob to drive! She goes crazy every time she spends 5 minutes with him, and for very, very good reason. A-

Cover Art: B
Story: B-
Dialogue: C+
Characters: A-
Comic Relief: B-
Overall: B-

I love SpongeBob Squarepants, though my younger brother (who is autistic) is by far the biggest fan in the entire family. He's got quite a handful of SpongeBob memorabilia, and he's forever reciting the names of certain episodes. (It's enough to drive one nuts at times.)

Probably my most favorite characters are SpongeBob and Patrick. The two of them can be pretty stupid at times, but that's what makes the whole cartoon so dang funny. And there are a few thematic elements here and there, but nothing too bad. I recommend this DVD to anyone who's a family person, and a big fan of cartoons.

I have to say, that I am unpleased with the lack of the pilot episode. But anyhow, we do end up getting some of the most classic and memorable episodes of Spongebob! The following are short reviews in which I will rate episodes individually.

Reef Blower: (4/5) Technically the second episode. The characters look a little more primitive than in subsequent episodes, which makes it interesting. Good humor!

Tea at the Teadome: (5/5) Exceptionally funny!

Bubblestand: (2/5) One of the weaker episodes of the season.

Ripped Pants: (5/5) Arguably a television classic!

Jellyfishing: (5/5) Very strong episode. Extremely hilarious!

Plankton!: (4/5) Introduces Plankton.

Naughty Nautical Neighbors: (5/5) Like "Jellyfishing", this is just HILARIOUS!

Boating School: (5/5) Bob and Patrick's mastermind plan comes to bite back at them!

Pizza Delivery: (5/5) A very unique episode in the whole series.

Home Sweet Pineapple: (4/5) Funny! Main point of interest is that we get to see Bob's parents.

Mermaidman and Barnacleboy: (5/5) Purely a classical episode!

Pickles: (3/5) This one is interesting, but not exceptional.

Hall Monitor: (3/5) It's okay.

Jellyfish Jam: (5/5) Silly and Funny!

Sandy's Rocket: (3/5) Average.

Squeaky Boots: (4/5) Above Average.

Nature Pants: (5/5) Classic, Funny, and has a good resolution.

Opposite Day: (2/5) In my opinion, this episode is weak.

Culture Shock: (4/5) Another Classic!

F.U.N.: (5/5) Very silly and f.u.n.n.y!

MuscleBob BuffPants: (4/5) Strong storyline.

Squidward, the Unfriendly Ghost: (4/5) Again, strong storyline, but not greatly funny.

The Chaperone: (5/5) Very funny. Good writing on this episode.

Employee of the Month: (4/5) Yet again ... good storyline, but not that funny.

Scaredy Pants:(5/5)HILARIOUS ENDING! My favorite of the season!

I Was a Teenage Gary: (5/5) As funny as its predecessor!

SB-129: (5/5) Exceptional storyline and humor! Superb animation, also.

Karate Choppers: (4/5) Very good writing and directing.

Sleepy Time: (5/5) Classical episode!

Suds: (4/5) Good laughs from Patrick's antics!

Valentine's Day: (3/5) Average; but still worth seeing.

The Paper: (2/5) Too over-the-top; like "Bubblestand".

Arrgh!: (5/5) Deserves a '5' for the storyline!

Rock Bottom: (2/5) Definatly not a better one. The very end is funny, though.

Texas: (4/5) Good storyline; good writing.

Walking Small: (4/5) Plankton is at his best thus far in the series.

Fools in April: (5/5) This begins to sum up the season with hilarious antics!

Neptune's Spatula: (5/5) Neptune's reactions are HILARIOUS! A classic episode.

Hooky: (3/5) Honestly, could have been better. The only truly funny part is the ironic ending.

Mermaidman and Barnacleboy II: (5/5) A worthy sequal to the first, and a worthy episode to sum up the season! I was very pleased with this one.

I had barely heard of Spongebob until the movie got shown while I was deployed abroad for a year with the National Guard. OK, so I'm 41, but yeah there is a kid in there somewhere ... and he loves this stuff. Which is the beauty & intelligence of Spongebob, because it works both as serious fun for kids and adults.

  So, then I found myself making it home from work in time to see new episodes ... and, finally, buying the DVDs of the first season. I have to really, really, really like something to get the DVD.

  Turns out, this set is great value, with a bunch of episodes plus extra features on three discs.

  It's just great stuff ... the characters, the animation, the stupid jokes, the scenarios. And what makes the whole deal is Spongebob himself, by turns nerdy, mischevious, funny, lost, brilliant, incompetent, etc. You get the picture: Complex.

  Spongebob is my new adult test: If you don't like it, it's time to quit taking yourself so seriously and lighten up.

  I generally find I don't like wild pop culture successes. I'm usually disappointed when I give into the marketing. Spongebob is a huge exception--it lives up to the hype. And the story behind how it happened -- told in one of the bonus features on this DVD set -- is just great. It reaffirms my belief that you generally can't set out some cynical masterplan to be truly successful: Ya gotta do what you love, and everything else will follow. Which pretty much sums up the Spongebob approach to life, I think.

Spongebob Squarepants, along with Fairly Odd Parents, is the best kid's animated series on TV today.  It has the shameless silliness for the kids and the witty cracks and well-evolved characters that adults can appreciate.  I am 30 and have watched these episodes numerous times and will continue to.  They are just funny.  I can relate to Squidward Tentacles' surly "whatever" attitude towards life.  The money-grubbing Mr. Krabs is hilarious as well as Spongebob's dim-witted friend, Patrick.  Plankton has to be funniest villain on television today!  Anyway, this series was spot on from the beginning to which the following first season episodes attest:

Disc 1:

Reef Blower: Contrary to previous reviews, "Help Wanted" (where Spongebob is hired at the Krusty Krab) is not included on this disc. The first episode shown here is the one where Spongebob (SB) and Patrick interrupt Squidward's quiet time by demonstrating the fun one can have with reef blowers.

Tea at the Teadome: Sandy Cheeks the Squirrel is introduced and Patrick gives SB misguided advice on how to handle himself in Sandy's air-filled home.

Bubblestand: Squidward ends up paying for bubble blowing lessons from SB.

Ripped Pants: A beach mishap gives SB his 15 minutes of fame which he soon abuses.

Jellyfishing: SB and Patrick want to give Squidward (in a full body cast after a bicycle accident) his "best day ever" by taking him jellyfishing.

Plankton: [w/ commentary] Introduces Mr. Krab's arch-enemy who tries to take-over SB's brain.

Naughty Nautical Neighbors: Squidward thinks its hilarious to break up SB and Patrick's friendship until they look to him to fill their friendship void.

Boating School: Patrick tries to radio instructions to SB so he will finally pass his boating test.

Pizza Delivery:  The Krusty Krab doesn't serve pizza. . . or does it?  For money, Mr. Krabs will have his crew deliver anything.

Home Sweet Pineapple: Nematodes destroy SB's pineapple and he might have to move back into his parent's house.

Mermaidman and Barnacleboy: Featuring the voices of Ernest Borgnine and Tim Conway.  SB and Patrick try to get their heroes out of retirement.

Pickles: SB is devastated when he forgets to put pickles on Bubble Bass' krabby patty.

Hall Monitor: SB's title for the day goes to his head.

Jellyfish Jam: SB finds out that wild jellyfish throw wild parties.

Sandy's Rocket: Sandy plans a trip to the moon in her rocket.  SB and Patrick get her there, as well as the rest of Bikini Bottom.

Squeaky Boots: Mr. Krab's convinces SB to give up his paycheck for Pearl's ill-received birthday gift.

Disc 2:

Nature Pants: SB wants to live among the jellyfish (don't we all).

Opposite Day: Squidward introduces a fake holiday to keep SB and Patrick away from him while he tries to sell his house.  Of course, it backfires.

Culture Shock: Squidward plans a talent show and hires a popular guy to clean up.

F.U.N.: Plankton and SB become friends?  I love the F.U.N. song (especially Plankton's version of the lyrics)!

MuscleBob BuffPant: SB buys blow-up muscle arms to impress Sandy and finds they are not too useful in weight-lifting competition.

Squidward the Unfriendly Ghost: Squidward doesn't mind that SB and Patrick think he's a ghost, until they decide he needs to go to the other side.

The Chaperone: SB takes Pearl to her prom.

Employee of the Month: SB and Squidward compete for the honor.

Scaredy Pants: The Flying Dutchman doesn't like SB dressing as him for Halloween.

I Was a Teenage Gary: Gary is left in the care of Squidward who forgets to feed him.  The ending to this one is hilarious.

SB-129: Squidward gets locked into a freezer and, when he is thawed out, finds himself in the future with his two biggest nightmares worse than ever.

Karate Choppers: [w/ commentaries] Mr. Krabs orders SB to stop playing karate.

Sleepy Time: SB enters the dreams of select Bikini Bottom residents; much to their nightmares.

Suds: Patrick tries various techniques to cure SB of the suds so he will not have to go to the dreaded doctor.

Valentine's Day: When SB's valentine delivery to Patrick is delayed, Patrick completely freaks out.

The Paper: Squidward is so impressed with what SB can do with a gum wrapper he threw away, he trades everything he owns to get it back. Then he finds it is just not the same.

Disc 3:

Arrgh!: Mr. Krabs takes the board game Treasure Hunt a little too seriously.

Rock Bottom: SB gets off the bus at the wrong stop and finds himself in strange territory with terrible bus service.

Texas: One of my favorites.  SB and Patrick try to convince the homesick Sandy that Bikini Bottom is her really home.

Walking Small: Plankton hopes he can recruit SB to clear the beach for the construction of his Chum Bucket Mega-Bucket.

Fools in April: Annoyed by SB's constant April tomfoolery, Squidward goes too far in getting him back.

Neptune's Spatula: Another fave of mine.  Neptune is skeptical that SB pulled the mythical spatula from the ancient grease.

Hooky: When SB does not heed his boss' advice about staying away from fishing hooks, Mr. Krabs must teach him a lesson.

Mermaidman and Barnacleboy II: SB wins the Conch Signal and runs his heroes ragged with trivial tasks.

This disc includes lots of extras including (but not limited to) interviews with the actors who supply the voices, a history of the show, Violent Femmes sing Spongebob, and a Patchy the Pirate-hosted Bikini Bottom tour (curiously, Patrick's rock is not included).

Yes Patrick we can!  Over a year from the release date of the first Spongebob Squarepants DVD (Nautical Nonsense/Sponge Buddies) comes what all fans wanted from the beginning:  The Complete First Season, all 40 episodes!  I like many others grabbed up the first few compilation discs like so many Krabby patties with extra pickles (I only bought 4) all the time wondering why in the world would such a popular cartoon series not immediately have season sets?  Where in the world is the Krabby Patty Value Meal if you catch my drift? The truth of the matter is the season sets on DVD were probably always planned, but then why spend a year releasing various "themed" collections with what will eventually appear on the complete sets?  Becau$e $pongebob make$ money!  Yes it's greedy and it only makes sense if you look at it that way.  With Season One on the shelf and Season two around the corner there really is no reason to continue buying or recommend buying the compilations.  There are 10 currently available with an 11th due out soon.  Which all together covers over 100 episodes of the roughly 120 that make up seasons 1 thru 3.  If you're a casual fan, by all means keep up with the occasional collection dvd release, but if you're a completist your journey through Bikini Bottom and all of it's watery and wiggly inhabitants begins here matey!  All 40 episodes spread over three discs in a delightful green box with our beloved yellow sponge (or is he cheese?) plastered on the cover.  Since you can get episode listings from other reviews and other places I'll do something a little different in dedication to the compilation buyers.

The 10 Spongebob DVDs currently available include 30 of the 40 Season 1 episodes.  So obviously if you've bought all these I can't recommend you go spend the money for this season set to get the 10 episodes you don't have.  However if you are like me and you've only bought say the first 4, then you only have 16 of the first season episodes.  So by getting the Season 1 box set you'll be gaining 24 episodes you don't have.  Of course I realize that everyone may have different discs so here is the run down on how many each of the compilation discs have in terms of season 1 episodes:

Nautical Nonsense/Sponge Buddies: 5

Halloween: 3

Sea Stories: 3

Tales from the Deep: 5

Lost at Sea: 5

Tide and Seek: 2

Christmas: 2

The Seascape Capers: 1

Spongebob goes prehistoric: 2

SpongeGuard on duty: 2

Sponge for Hire: 0

SPONGEBOB IS ONE OF THE BEST CARTOONS EVER CREATED!!! There I said it & I mean it. A lot of people (not Spongebob fans of course) think this cartoon is totally senseless. But the ones I've actually been able to sit down & force to watch a few episodes have happily converted.  Okay the premise is ridiculous, but that's the fun of it & the characters are great. Don't mind that a lot of the things that happen don't make sense, it's a CARTOON. Even the characters make fun of themselves, like how can they hear without ears & how can they make fire if they're under water? It's also kind of educational. WHAT!! Did I say "EDUCATIONAL"? YES!! Just watch the episodes & see what our favorite sponge & friends learn about lying, stealing, cheating, greed & being mean to friends & you'll see what I mean. Of course the lessons aren't thrown in your face, but they're in there & my son understands. It makes me a proud Spongebob fan (& father) when my (now six-year old) son looks at me & says, "Mr. Krabs only loves money & that's bad." Or "Spongebob wouldn't have gone through all that if he didn't lie."  I know there are still skeptics out there (I was one) but a cartoon like this doesn't just become what it is without there being "something" special about it. One of my favorite things on DVD's are the "behind the scenes" & "making of" features & this DVD has it's own list of features that gives people like me more insight & understanding of what goes into making Spongebob special. This is a great buy! So stop reading & buy it! BUY IT NOW! GO AHEAD!!

I purchased this DVD collection because of my love of Spongebob. This collection is only the first season so there are episodes on the individual releases that are not on this one. However, this collection is not 'complete'. The pilot episode 'Help Wanted' was left out. The pilot episode shows where spongebob gets ready to apply for his job at the Krusty Krab. Then has to prove himself, as the great fry cook he is, by preparing krabby patties for a mass of customers. I'm not sure how you could call it complete w/out it. The missing episode was the only disappointing factor of this set. I am a huge fan of Spongebob as are my kids!!
the reason help wanted isn't on the DVD set is because there was a problem with securing rights, probably the song at the end of the episode

So I've bought all the DVD's seperate plus the complete season and I'm a bit disappointed. There are just as many episodes on the single purchased dvd's that are not on the complete set, that the complete set has which are unique to it. Another words, buying the complete season one was not a superset of anything I already had.
There's been atleast one episode on each one of my single DVD which didn't exist on the complete set. I guess nickeleon makes you buy everything they release to be able to get a complete set.
If I was rating the boxset compared to what has been released, I would only give it 3/5, but since I have to give it a rating on the actual episodes on the boxset, and I love spongebob, I have to give it 5/5.
So, I'll compromise. 4/5

I first saw this show with my little cousin and I think I found it funnier than she did! This show is great for kids and adults alike. SpongeBob is just an innocent little sponge that wants to be friends with everyone and doesn't have a mean bone in his body...after all he is a sponge. I am suprised how entertaining this cartoon is. It sort of harkens back to the old Loony Toons cartoons. The DVD is packed with 40 episodes of SpongeBob mahem. There is a "Play All" option although I don't believe any full grown adult could sit through 40 staight episodes of SpongeBob. There are a few little behind the scenes features that are pretty interesting. The Violent Femmes promo is a suprising yet appreciated extra. I took a star off for the lack of commentaries. The segments are only 15-20 minutes long, they could have had more commentaries than two. Overall, it is a nice little DVD set that is a must for the SpongeBob fans.

What can I say?
All 40 episodes plus the bonus features. If you are in any way a Spongebob fan, get it!!!
I've seen most of the episodes on tv, but the special features are my favourite. It's great to put a face to the voices. I've seen Tom Kenny (Spongebob) on stage twice at Montreal's Just for laughs, years ago. It was very hard to make the connection between Tom Kenny and Spongebob. He even shows you how he does that annoying laugh.
I don't know if this dvd is more for me or my daughter, but she'll probably win in the end.

Okay, i love this show.  But, it does get annoying, so i deducted one star.  I also noticed that the first season does not include the best episode of anything ever, "Sailor Mouth".  So i deducted one point..It doesn't really matter what i think  cause if you love Spongebob, you're gonna buy this anyway.

If you didn't know how popular Spongebob is than this is definite proof. The first ever Nick Toon to receive a complete Season 1 DVD release. This is almost unheard of in the world of 12 minute shorts made for children the age 5 and over. Unlike all the other Nick Toons Spongebob has hit a chord that hasn't been struck since the likes of Ren and Stimpy have graced our television sets. Its a shame we all bought the past releases thinking "well this is as good as it gets." I never saw this coming I am both shocked and happily surprised. Sure I feel ripped off, but I'm glad I can get all the episodes now. Those ten per episode discs were boggling my mind with no end as to how would I own them all?
Just release all three seasons within a reasonable time span and one day I will completely forgive them for misleading us with the single disc releases. Can't wait for the movie.

This release is much awaited by many spongebob fans across the world, especially after being teased with several spongebob releases with 10 random episodes each, finally u will be able to add the 1st complete season to your collection.  Just to correct one of the former reviews, the first season is not every spongebob episode known to date. The first season ran from July of 1999 until May 2000 and included 20 episodes, keep in mind every episode has 2 stories, so u can look at it as really getting 40 episodes.  ANyhoo this is an absolute must for any spongebob fan, don't waste your money on the silly 10 episode releases, just get the seasons as they are released.
